<p>Looking at our third model gives us one clue as to why the previous models on violent crime look the way they are. We can notice some similar visual patterns on the map on poverty; low poverty rates in New England and the midwest, and higher in the South and New Mexico.</p>
</section>
<section id="conclusion" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
<p>Some takeaways from my models are that it seems like different types of violent crime are linked geographically. I am curious if this trend holds up if I mapped out a single state and looked at individual counties. Another takeaway is that poverty is likely one explanatoy variable of violent crime. This could be useful for prediciting violent crime, and also for trying to reduce it. For future research, I wonder what other variables would be useful in the same way. Perhaps looking at economic opportunities? Jobs? Education? These are all factors I wonder about. I also wonder if there is a regression model that could be made to predict crime, and how many variables would go into the model to make it most accurate.</p>
<p>A few flaws in my research from this blog post: For one, the usdata is missing murder and aggravated assault data from Montana, Nebraska and Kentucky. Additionally, Hawaii and Alaska were not included on my maps. To have the most accurate analysis possible, it would be best to include these states.</p>


</section>
